      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral GPIOA",
        "description": "Read GPIOA registers (SVD-decoded) on the L476RG"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "Multiple probes are attached \u2014 I need to pick the right one. Let me list probes and check the project descriptor's board.\n**Yes.** On the NUCLEO-L476RG, USART2 uses PA2 (TX) and PA3 (RX), and GPIOA shows both pins correctly configured:\n\n| Pin | MODER | AFR | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| PA2 | `MODER2 = 0b10` | `AFRL2 = 7` | Alternate Function mode, **AF7 = USART2_TX** \u2705 |\n| PA3 | `MODER3 = 0b10` | `AFRL3 = 7` | Alternate Function mode, **AF7 = USART2_RX** \u2705 |\n\nSupporting detail: both pins are push-pull (`OTYPER = 0`), medium speed (`OSPEEDR = 0b01`), with pull-up enabled (`PUPDR = 0b01`) \u2014 a typical HAL UART init. PA3's input data bit reads high (`IDR3 = 1`), consistent with an idle UART RX line.\n\nSo the GPIO side of USART2 is fully configured for alternate function. (Note: the bench had two probes attached \u2014 I targeted the L476RG via its probe SN `066DFF...1514`, matching the project descriptor; the attach was no-reset, so this is live state.)"
}